Mar 4 2009	Great location and nicely appointed	We stayed in this hotel as part of the Friendly Planet Tour. Based on the price we paid for the entire tour (10 days for $1299), I did not expect much from the hotels. While this hotel wasn't perfect, I was pleasantly suprised with its amenities:POSITIVES:- Location: This place has a great location within walking distance to Tienanmam Square (about 1.3 miles), Wangfujing Street (about 1.0 mile), Forbidden City (about 1.3 miles) and the Silk Market (the highlight of Beijing bargin shopping - about 1.0 mile). It is also convenient to the subway station so that you can easily explore other areas of the city without reliance upon cabs (which almost never speak english). In addition, there is a mall and grocery store directly accross the street and several western eating places (Subway, McDonalds, Papa John's Pizza, TGI Fridays) with a 5 minute walk. - Room: The room was very nicely appointed. My room had two twin beds, a desk, Flatscreen TV and a couple of cosy chairs. The bathroom was very nice, marble floors and countertops, a spacious shower with decent water pressure and the hotel provided nice amenities like a new toothbrush and toothpaste and bottle water on a daily basis. - Buffet: With our tour, every morning we were provided a western style buffet breakfast. It was very similar to the buffets you come to find in, for example, Las Vegas. The buffet had all the food we are used to: omelets cooked to order, pancakes (but no syrup), bacon, toast, a wide selection of fresh fruit, yogurt, cereal, coffee and 3 or 4 different juices. In addition to western food, the buffet had a wide selection of traditional chinese dishes including dumplings, noodles and other things that I didn't try because I didn't know what they were. While going into the trip I was very worried about the food in China generally, I had no worries eating almost everything at this buffet as it was very clean and nobody in our tour got sick from any of the food we ate. - Money exchange: As easy as it gets! Just give your room number and the amount you want to convert and they do it WITHOUT a service charge. Everytime we did it the girl spoke perfect English and wasquick, efficient and extremely nice. NEUTRALS:- Bed: If you are tall like me you might find sleeping in China challanging as the beds tend to be very short. Also the beds in China are MUCH firmer than most of us westerners are used to. - Cleanliness: While the lobby and other common areas of the hotel were spotless and the lobby bathrooms were impecible, the hallways leading to the rooms were a tas bit worn and smelled musty. Luckily, that musty smell did not invade the rooms. - View: The view from the window was a nice view of the intersection (nothing spectacular); however, the windows were practically floor to ceiling.- Lobby: Very large and nicely decorated BUT no place to sit and relax other than the bar on the second floor. NEGATIVES:- Business Center: Extremely overpriced. Internet was basically $13/ hour in the hotel's business center. Considering the internet at the internet cafe accross the street was like .50 cents per hour it seemed like a rip off. - Bar: The bar is also extremely overpriced. Most cocktails including bear were between $9 and $11. Considering the same beer is .30 per bottle at the supermarket accross the street, its amazing they can get away with charging $10 per bottle in the bar. In addition, they impose an automatic gratuity of 15%, which in a country which they say tipping is not the norm nor the custom, was a bit suprising. This is the only place in all of China that automatically added a tip. SUMMARY:I would definatelt recommend a stay at this hotel if you are looking for a place to explore Beijing from but demand some comforts that you are used to in the United States.	
